    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-07-06T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-07-06T18:00:00-05:00" n="176"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d176">
                <head>176. Telegram 1730 From the Embassy in Costa Rica to the Department of
                        State<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d176fn1">Source: National Archives,
                        RG 59, Central Files 1970–73, <gloss target="#POL1">POL</gloss> 29 COSTA
                        RICA. Confidential; Priority. It was repeated to Guatemala City, La Paz,
                        Madrid, Lima, Managua, Santiago, San Salvador, Tegucigalpa, and <gloss
                            target="#USCINCSO1">USCINCSO</gloss>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d176fn2">President <persName
                            corresp="#p_FFJ1">Figueres</persName> told the Embassy that the Costa
                        Rican Government was still studying a plan to arrange the escape of
                        Sandinista captive Carlos Fonseca Amador to a third country.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>San Jose</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-07-06T23:00:00+00:00">July 6, 1970, 2300Z</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <pb facs="d176-1" n="1" xml:id="pg_d176-1"/>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Subject:</head>
                    <item>Carlos Fonseca Amador</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>Ref:</head>
                    <item>San Jose 1621</item>
                </list>
                <p>1. President Figueres told me yesterday me yesterday <gloss target="#GOCR1"
                        >GOCR</gloss> still studying plan for Fonseca’s “escape” to third country.
                    Fonseca had turned down plan which included momentary asylum in Chilean Embassy
                    San Jose because he “would lose face” asking for asylum.</p>
                <p>2. Figueres indicated latest thinking was to deliver Fonseca directly to Cuba via
                    a secret LACSA flight. He might attempt arrange exchange for one of Cubans
                    imprisoned by <persName corresp="#p_CRF1">Castro</persName>.</p>
                <p>3. If Cuba asylum could not be arranged, Chile, Bolivia, and Peru remained other
                    countries which might accept Fonseca. Spain remained a possibility, although
                    President indicated CR FonOff had not yet approached Spanish on this matter.</p>
                <p>4. Figueres promised keep Embassy informed developments.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_PWC1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Ploeser</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
